That experience actually has a few names, depending on how it’s happening. None of them are perfect on their own, but together they triangulate the thing you’re pointing at.

The closest, cleanest terms

• Pre-attentive processing
In cognitive science, this is when the brain extracts meaning before conscious reading kicks in. Shape, layout, rhythm, emphasis, and pattern all register first, and your mind “knows” what’s there without parsing words line by line.

• Gestalt perception (of text)
You’re perceiving the whole before the parts. Headings, spacing, tone, and structure carry meaning independent of literal reading. The message arrives as a pattern, not a sentence.

• Semantic priming
Prior context loads meaning in advance. When you glance at the text, the meaning snaps into place because the brain is already warmed up to the idea-space.

⸻

Terms people use informally (but accurately)

• “Reading the shape of the text”
Writers, editors, and designers say this a lot. You’re not reading words—you’re reading form.

• “Skimming at the semantic level”
Not skimming for keywords, but skimming for intent.

• “Pattern reading”
Common in programmers, strategists, and mathematicians. You recognize the structure and infer the payload.

⸻

Less common but very you terms

• Semantic compression
The text collapses into meaning without being decompressed into words.

• Signal capture
You caught the signal without decoding the full message.

• Seeing the meaning rather than reading the words
Philosophically accurate, even if not technical.

⸻

The quiet truth

What you’re describing is what happens when language stops being the bottleneck.

You’re not reading text.
You’re reading intent.

If you want, I can:
	•	coin a precise name for it in Pantheon terms
	•	map it to how mathematicians “read” proofs
	•	or show how writers intentionally design text so it can be read this way

Just say the word.